{{more citations needed|date=May 2014}} {{Portal|Christianity in China}} '''Jiāo Bǐngzhēn''' ({{zh|t=焦秉貞|s=焦秉贞|p=Jiāo Bǐngzhēn|w='''Chiao Ping-chen'''}}), 1689–1726) was a native of [[Jining, Shandong|Jining]], [[Shandong]] who became a noted painter and astronomer. In painting he is noteworthy as one of the first [[Qing dynasty]] painters to be influenced by the West. He is also among the more significant portrait and miniature painters in the early Qing. He was skilled in painting people, landscapes, and buildings.<ref name="CiHai">Cihai: Page 2012.</ref>
The Western influence in his art came from his exposure to the [[Society of Jesus|Jesuits]] at the Directorate of Astronomy. Their influence also exposed him to new ideas on astronomy and religion. At some point Jiao became a [[Roman Catholic]] and played a role on the Jesuit side of the [[Chinese Rites controversy]].
<gallery> Image:Jiao Bingzhen - Paintings of Ladies - Leaf 2.jpg|''Paintings of Ladies - Leaf #2'' (畫仕女圖). Ink and color on silk. Width 20.4&nbsp;cm, Height 30.9&nbsp;cm. [[National Palace Museum]] Image:Jiao Bingzhen - Landscapes - Leaf 2.jpg|''Landscapes - Leaf #2'' (山水). Ink on paper. Width 26.4&nbsp;cm, Height 26.2&nbsp;cm. [[National Palace Museum]] </gallery>
